{"title_page": "Central Vanuatu languages", "text_new": "{{short description|Subgroup of the Oceanic branch of the Austronesian language family}}\n{{Infobox language family\n|name=Central Vanuatu \n|altname=\n|region=[[Vanuatu]]\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] \n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam6=\n|glotto=cent2269\n|glottorefname=Central Vanuatu\n}}\nThe '''Central Vanuatu languages''' form a [[linkage (linguistics)|linkage]] of [[Southern Oceanic languages]] spoken in central [[Vanuatu]].\n\n==Languages==\n===Clark (2009)===\nClark (2009) provides the following classification of the Central Vanuatu languages, divided into geographic areas.<ref name=\"Clark-Vanuatu\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=Ross |date=2009 |title=Leo Tuai: A comparative lexical study of North and Central Vanuatu languages |location=Canberra |publisher=Pacific Linguistics}}</ref> Outlier (aberrant) languages identified by Clark (2009) are in ''italics''. Clark's Central Vanuatu branch is wider in scope, including not only the Shepherd\u2013Efate languages, but also the [[Malakula languages|Malakula]] and Ambrym\u2013Paama\u2013Epi languages.\n\n*Central Vanuatu\n**'''[[Malakula languages]]'''\n***[[Northeast Malakula language|Northeast Malakula]] ([[Uripiv language|Uripiv]]), [[Vao language|Vao]], [[Vovo language|Vovo]]; ''[[Mpotovoro language|Mpotovoro]]''\n***''[[Dirak language|Dirak]]'', ''[[Malua Bay language|Malua Bay]]''\n***''[[V'\u00ebnen Taut language|V\u2019\u00ebnen Taut]]'', ''[[Tape language|Tape]]''\n***''[[Larevat language|Larevat]]'', ''[[Neve'ei language|Neve\u2019ei]]'', ''[[Naman language|Naman]]''\n***''[[Navava language|Navava]]'', ''[[Nevwervwer language|Nevwervwer]]''\n***[[Unua language|Unua]]-[[Pangkumu language|Pangkumu]]\n***[[Banam Bay language|Banam Bay]], [[Aulua language|Aulua]]\n***[[Lendamboi language|Lendamboi]]; ''[[Nasarian language|Nasarian]]''\n***[[Axamb language|Axamb]], [[Avok language|Avok]], [[Maskelynes language|Maskelynes]], [[Port Sandwich language|Port Sandwich]]\n***[[Sinesip language|Sinesip]], [[Naha'ai language|Naha\u2019ai]]; ''[[Ninde language|Ninde]]''\n**'''Ambrym\u2013Paama\u2013[[Epi languages|Epi]]''' area\n***'''[[Ambrym Island]]''': [[North Ambrym language|North Ambrym]], [[West Ambrym language|West Ambrym]], [[South Ambrym language|South Ambrym]]\n***'''[[Paama Island]]''': [[Southeast Ambrym language|Southeast Ambrym]], [[Paamese language|Paamese]]\n***'''[[Epi Island]]''': [[Lewo language|Lewo]], [[Lamen language|Lamen]], [[Bierebo language|Bierebo]], [[Baki language|Baki]]\n***'''[[Epi Island]]''': [[Mkir language|Mkir]], [[Bieria language|Bieria]]\n**'''Shepherd\u2013Efate''' area\n***'''[[Shepherd Islands]]''': [[Nakanamanga language|Nakanamanga]] ([[Nguna language|Nguna]]); ''[[Namakir language|Namakir]]''\n***'''[[Efate Island]]''': [[South Efate language|South Efate]]\n\nAccording to [[Nicholas Thieberger|Thieberger]], ''[[Efatese language|Efatese]]'' is an artificial mixture of the languages of Efate.\n\n===Fran\u00e7ois (2015)===\nThe following list of 19 Central Vanuatu languages (excluding the [[Malakula languages]]) is from Fran\u00e7ois ([[#density|2015]]:18-21).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! No. !! Language !! Other names !! Speakers !! [[Ethnologue]] !! [[ISO 639-3]] !! Region\n|-\n| 107 || [[North Ambrym language|North Ambrym]] ||  || 5250 || {{ethnolink|mmg}} || [[ISO 639:mmg|mmg]] || [[Ambrym]]\n|-\n| 108 || [[Orkon language|Orkon]] || [[Fanbak language|Fanbak]] || 30 ||  ||  || [[Ambrym]]\n|-\n| 109 || [[Southeast Ambrym language|Southeast Ambrym]] ||  || 3700 || {{ethnolink|tvk}} || [[ISO 639:tvk|tvk]] || [[Ambrym]]\n|-\n| 110 || [[Daakie language|Daakie]] || [[Port Vato language|Port Vato]] || 1300 || {{ethnolink|ptv}} || [[ISO 639:ptv|ptv]] || [[Ambrym]]\n|-\n| 111 || [[Daakaka language|Daakaka]] || [[South Ambrym language|South Ambrym]], [[Baiap lan